    <h1>CSC Web Portal</h1>

    <section id="internet">
        <h2>Internet vs Ethernet</h2>
        <p><strong>Internet:</strong> A global network that connects millions of devices worldwide using TCP/IP
            protocols.</p>
        <p><strong>Ethernet:</strong> A local area network (LAN) technology used to connect devices in close proximity
            with wired connections.</p>
        <p><strong>Key Differences:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Internet: Global, public, usually wireless</li>
            <li>Ethernet: Local, private, wired, faster and more stable</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="virtualization">
        <h2>Virtualization</h2>
        <p>Virtualization allows running multiple operating systems on a single physical machine using virtual machines
            (VMs).</p>
        <p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Full virtualization</li>
            <li>Paravirtualization</li>
            <li>OS-level virtualization</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Benefits:</strong> Cost savings, test environments, isolation, efficient resource usage.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="win10">
        <h2>Installing Windows 10 on Oracle VirtualBox</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Download VirtualBox and Windows 10 ISO.</li>
            <li>Create a new VM in VirtualBox.</li>
            <li>Assign memory and storage.</li>
            <li>Attach Windows ISO to virtual optical drive.</li>
            <li>Start VM and follow Windows installer.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section id="ubuntu">
        <h2>Installing Ubuntu on Oracle VirtualBox</h2>
        <ol>
            <li>Download Ubuntu ISO.</li>
            <li>Open VirtualBox ‚Üí New ‚Üí "Ubuntu".</li>
            <li>Set memory (2GB+), disk (25GB+), and boot with Ubuntu ISO.</li>
            <li>Install Ubuntu by following GUI steps.</li>
            <li>Install Guest Additions (for screen resize, clipboard):</li>
        </ol>
        <pre>sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential dkms linux-headers-$(uname -r)</pre>
    </section>

    <section id="tools">
        <h2>Ubuntu Diagnostic Tools (Lab 4)</h2>
        <p><strong class="highlight">Hardware:</strong> lshw, lscpu, lsblk, lspci, lsusb, hwinfo, dmidecode</p>
        <p><strong class="highlight">Performance:</strong> top, htop, glances, vmstat, iotop</p>
        <p><strong class="highlight">Network:</strong> ping, traceroute, iftop, nethogs, ip, nmcli</p>
        <p><strong class="highlight">Logs:</strong> journalctl, dmesg, /var/log</p>
        <p><strong class="highlight">Filesystem:</strong> df, du, fsck, badblocks</p>
        <p><strong class="highlight">Boot/Service:</strong> systemctl, update-grub, systemd-analyze</p>
    </section>

    <section id="lab5">
        <h2>Lab 5 ‚Äì Web and File Servers on Ubuntu</h2>
        <h3>üñ• Web Server (Apache)</h3>
        <pre>sudo apt update
sudo apt install apache2 -y
sudo systemctl enable apache2
sudo systemctl start apache2</pre>

        <h3>üìÅ File Sharing with Samba</h3>
        <pre>sudo apt install samba -y
sudo mkdir -p /srv/samba/shared
sudo chmod 2775 /srv/samba/shared
sudo chown nobody:nogroup /srv/samba/shared

# Add to /etc/samba/smb.conf
[SharedFiles]
   path = /srv/samba/shared
   browseable = yes
   read only = no
   guest ok = yes

sudo systemctl restart smbd
sudo ufw allow 'Samba'</pre>

        <h3>üìÅ File Sharing with NFS</h3>
        <pre>sudo apt install nfs-kernel-server -y
sudo mkdir -p /srv/nfs/shared
sudo chown nobody:nogroup /srv/nfs/shared

# Add to /etc/exports
/srv/nfs/shared 192.168.1.0/24(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)

sudo exportfs -a
sudo systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server
sudo ufw allow from 192.168.1.0/24 to any port nfs</pre>
    </section>

    <section id="concurrency">
        <h2>Concurrency</h2>
        <p>Concurrency is the ability of an operating system to handle multiple tasks at once. It is a key concept in
            process scheduling and multitasking.</p>
        <p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Running multiple browser tabs</li>
            <li>Background software updates</li>
            <li>Multi-threaded server applications</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

